				\begin{document} $$I_{i}=\frac{x_{i}-\overline{x}}{S^{2}}\sum\limits_{j}W_{ij}\left(x_{j}-\overline{x}\right), $$ \end{document}Ii=xi−x¯S2∑jWijxj−x¯, where S2 is the variance of x. A positive or negative value of Ii means spatial clustering of similar or dissimilar incidence rate, which allows to classify regions into five categories: high-high, low-low, high-low, low-high, and non-significant. The high-high and low-low areas indicated the hot and cold spots of dengue incidence, respectively. While the high-low and low-high areas were the outliers [16].

